===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Any of various land-dwelling [[reptile]]s, of the [[family]] [[Testudinidae]] {{lb|en|chiefly|North America}} or the order [[Testudines]] {{lb|en|chiefly|UK}}, whose body is enclosed in a [[shell]] ([[carapace]] plus [[plastron]]). The animal can [[withdraw]] its head and four legs partially into the shell, providing some [[protection]] from [[predator]]s.
#: {{syn|en|shellpad|q=obsolete}}

====Usage notes====
Differences exist in usage of the common terms {{m|en|turtle}}, {{m|en|tortoise}}, and {{m|en|terrapin}}, depending on the variety of English being used. In American usage, {{m|en|turtle}} is often a general term; {{m|en|tortoise}} is used only in reference to terrestrial turtles or, more narrowly, only those members of {{l|mul|Testudinidae}}, the family of modern land tortoises; and {{m|en|terrapin}} may refer to turtles that are small and live in fresh and brackish water.

British usage, by contrast, tends not to use {{m|en|turtle}} as a generic term for all members of the order but instead as a synonym for ''sea turtle'' specifically, and also applies the term {{m|en|tortoise|tortoises}} broadly to all land-dwelling members of the order {{l|mul|Testudines}}, regardless of whether they are actually members of the family {{l|mul|Testudinidae}}.

Land tortoises are not native to Australia, yet traditionally freshwater turtles have been called {{m|en|tortoise|tortoises}} in Australia.

